Tutorial 3 - Interactivity with Pluto.jl

6 steps

Pluto.jl is a modern, interactive development environment for the Julia programming language. It combines the power of Julia with the convenience of a notebook interface, making it easy to explore, analyze, and visualize data, and rapidly develop and test code.

You will learn some basic Pluto.jl features in this quest!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the 🆘 | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

Prerequisites

Required to have finished Tutorials/Quests 1 and 2 on Learn.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

Required to have finished Tutorials 1 and 2 on Learn.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Learn how to install Pluto.jl.
  • Execute Julia code inside Pluto.
  • Create an interactive slider inside Pluto.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: Preparing Your Pluto Notebook

    From your prepared development environment from Tutorials 1 and 2, close all running terminals and open a new terminal. Run the following shell command to install Pluto.jl.

    julia --project=@notebooks

    This will create a separate stand-alone environment called notebooks. It won't be present in your project but in a special directory in Julia i.e. ~/.julia/environments.

    Head to the pkg> REPL by pressing ] right bracket on your keyboard. Run the following on the pkg> REPL.

    add Pluto

    To check if it's installed correctly, on the pkg> REPL, run the following command.

    status

    You should have a similar output like below.

    Status `~/.julia/environments/notebooks/Project.toml`
  [c3e4b0f8] Pluto v0.20.4

    Go back to the julia> REPL by deleting the prompt you have written previously, if there are, with the backspace key. Then run the following code to the julia> REPL.

    using Pluto
Pluto.run()
    Plain text

    For local users, you just have to open the indicated URL. But for GitHub Codespaces, you have to open a forwarded address.

    Your forwarded address can be found at the Ports tab then in the Forwarded Address column in VSCode.

    Your full URL for your Pluto notebook will look similar to https://special-waffle-qj6rqp5j5fxp4g-1234.app.github.dev/?secret=IrMxs2vN. The secret is indicated by the "?secret=SomeKey".

    ℹ️ If you don't want to run Pluto that requires a secret key, you can use this alternative instead. Just stop your existing Pluto instance in the julia> REPL by pressing Ctrl key and the c key together on your keyboard then run the following code.

    import Pluto;
Pluto.run(;require_secret_for_access=false)
    Plain text

    ⚠️ Be warned that whenever you go to another window, codespaces might see it that you are inactive, thus, automatically stopping your codespace. You have to restart it if it occurs and re-run Pluto again, for example, by running the following shell command.

    julia --project=@notebooks -e "import Pluto; Pluto.run(;require_secret_for_access=false)"

    Select notebook.jl in the Pluto notebook homepage then click the "Run notebook code" button on the upper-right of your notebook.

    What is Pluto?

    Pluto.jl's interactivity sets it apart from traditional programming environments. It allows you to execute code and see the results immediately, without having to compile or run the entire program. This makes it ideal for exploratory programming, where you want to try out different ideas and see the results in real time.

    Pluto.jl notebooks are made up of cells, which can contain code, text, or Markdown. Code cells can be executed individually or in sequence, and the results are displayed below the cell. This allows you to easily experiment with different code snippets and see how they affect the output.

    Pluto allows ease of data exploration and also storing the code itself as a set of Julia code for later reuse.

    Let's try executing Julia code in the next step.

  • Step 2: Executing Some Code in Pluto notebooks

    In your Pluto notebook web app, click the "Create a new notebook" button. This will load a new notebook on Pluto.

    Click the Save notebook query to and name it as notebook.jl. Click the button Choose to save the file.

    Click Enter cell code and write the following code.

    println("Hello, World!")
    Plain text

    Click the ▷ button on the bottom right corner of your cell or by pressing Shift key and Enter key together on your keyboard to run the code cell. It should output "Hello, World!".

    To create a new code cell, hover over the existing code cell and a plus + button will appear on the bottom left corner of the existing code cell. There is also a plus button on the top right corner. It's used to create a new code cell above the hovered cell. Click the plus button on the bottom left corner. This creates a new cell at the bottom of the previous cell. You can also just press the Ctrl key and the Enter key together on your keyboard to create a new cell at the bottom.

    On the new cell, write the following code.

    hello(x) = println("Hello, $(x)!")
hello("Stackie")
    Plain text

    You should get an error message that multiple expressions are not allowed.

    This means that each code cell is only for one code statement in Pluto.

    Create a new cell and move the hello("Stackie") code over. Then head back to the code cell where the hello function is located then run the code cell.

    The cell with the hello("Stackie") function call should output Hello, Stackie!.

    Watch the video below to get familiar with Pluto notebooks for this step.

    You will also notice in the video that you can run multiple statements as long as it is wrapped within a begin-end block.

    Let's move forward and learn how to install packages, DataFrames.jl and CSV.jl in the next step.

  • Step 3: DataFrames.jl and CSV.jl in Pluto notebooks

    DataFrames.jl and CSV.jl are popular Julia packages for managing CSV data and tabulated data in Julia. They're commonly used together to read CSV files and to create tables from CSV files.

    CSV or comma-separated value is a data format commonly used for storing data as text files. Each comma represents a split between two columns of data.

    You will be using COVID-19 data collected and archived by the World Health Organization. Head to https://data.who.int/dashboards/covid19/data and click the "Weekly COVID-19 cases by date" Download button. See screenshot below to see what it looks like.

    Download the CSV file and move it to the root directory of your project. To download in GitHub Codespaces, copy the link instead from the download button and run the following command on the terminal.

    curl -fsSLO https://srhdpeuwpubsa.blob.core.windows.net/whdh/COVID/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv

    Your URL might look different so please double check and replace as needed with your copied link. It will save the file with the filename WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv.

    Head back to your existing Pluto notebook and delete cells. Check out the following short video below to know how to.

    Delete all cells and create a new cell, if a cell does not exist.

    Write the following code to the new code cell.

    begin
	using DataFrames
	using CSV
end
    Plain text

    Click the ▷ button on the bottom right corner of your cell or by pressing Shift key and Enter key together on your keyboard to run the code cell. You should have an output similar to the screenshot below.

    Wait for it until it turns into a check mark ✔️.

    Create a new cell and write the following code to the code cell.

    df = CSV.read("WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv", DataFrame)
    Plain text

    Click the ▷ button on the bottom right corner of your cell or by pressing Shift key and Enter key together on your keyboard to run the code cell. It should output tabulated data above the cell similar to the screenshot below.

    You have finally created a variable called df which holds the CSV data as a DataFrame object.

    Create a new code cell. Write the following code to the new code cell.

    df.Country_code === df[!, "Country_code"]
    Plain text

    Click the ▷ button on the bottom right corner of your cell or by pressing Shift key and Enter key together on your keyboard to run the code cell. It should output "true".

    The code previously is showing you that there are two different syntax i.e. to get to the "Country_code" column. It's preferred to use the right side of the === to get to a column because some columns have column names with spaces (e.g. "Country_code" vs "Country code").

    Although the focus of this quest is about Pluto, Pluto notebooks are usually used with CSV and DataFrames. This step won't cover deeply about CSV and DataFrames. Let's move along and just run some code!

    To know more about CSV and DataFrames packages in Julia, check out the links below.

    • https://dataframes.juliadata.org/stable/man/getting_started/
    • https://csv.juliadata.org/stable/#

    Now, you will filter the data to select only COVID cases from Singapore. To do this, create a new code cell and enter the following code:

    equals_sg(x::AbstractString) = x == "SG"
    Plain text

    This function will be used to filter data with the filter method.

    Create a new code cell. Write the following code.

    sg_data = filter(:Country_code => equals_sg, df)
    Plain text

    The data with the country code "SG" for Singapore should be the only data selected. This data will then be plotted using Plots.jl in the next step.

  • Step 4: Using Plots.jl in Pluto notebooks

    Pluto.jl allows you to use Plots.jl to generate graphs and plot data inside a Pluto notebook.

    First, let's only select the relevant columns for Singapore's COVID-19 data, the date and the cumulative number of cases. Write the following lines of code, each line in different code cells but in the order of occurrence.

    dates = sg_data[!, "Date_reported"]
cumulative_cases = sg_data[!, "Cumulative_cases"]
using Plots  # This will install plots
    Plain text

    Check out the screenshot below for what each line looks like in different code cells.

    Run each cell. Wait for Plots.jl to get a ✔️. Once it's installed, write the following code into another code cell.

    cumulative_data_plotted_over_date = plot(dates, cumulative_cases)
    Plain text

    You should get a generated image of plotted data. It should look similar to the image below.

    You can also add a title, and labels for the x and y axes. Write the new code on another cell.

    plot!(cumulative_data_plotted_over_date, title="Singapore COVID-19 Cases 2020-2025", xlabel="Dates", ylabel="Cumulative Number of Cases")
    Plain text

    The differences between plot and plot! is that the latter will update the original plot while the former will generate a new plot. This means that the variable cumulative_data_plotted_over_date will also update. Your new plot image will look like this.

    It now contains a title, a label for the x-axis, and a label for the y-axis.

  • Step 5: Creating A Slider

    Let's create a slider to adjust the ranges of the dates from the previous step. To add interactive sliders, write the following code to another cell.

    using PlutoUI
    Plain text

    This will install PlutoUI.jl which is a Pluto notebook plugin to add more interactivity such as buttons and sliders.

    Let's create a simple interactive slider. Write the following code to another cell.

    @bind slider_value Slider(0:10:1000)
    Plain text

    Julia's metaprogramming capabilities enable the @bind macro, which is necessary for initializing the interactive slider. Macros, look similar to functions, but instead of executing code, they generate code; thus, the @bind macro generates the code for the slider.

    Write this block of code in another cell.

    md"""
### Slider Value Now At $(slider_value)
"""
    Plain text

    The md keyword is another feature in Pluto. It allows you to write markdown inside string blocks (or multi-line strings; strings that are wrapped around triple double-quotes """).

    Run each code cell and interact with the slider like dragging it from left to right or right to left.

    Let's create a slider for the dates. Write the following code to another cell.

    @bind date_slider_index Slider(1:length(dates))
    Plain text

    Write this block of code in another cell.

    md"""
### The date is now $(dates[date_slider_index])
"""
    Plain text

    Write this line of code in another cell.

    new_plot = plot(dates[date_slider_index:end], cumulative_cases[date_slider_index:end], title="Singapore COVID-19 Cases 2020-2025", xlabel="Dates", ylabel="Cumulative Number of Cases")
    Plain text

    Run each new cell. Watch the video below to see the results!

  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    You have reached the end! Now to finish this tutorial, you have to carefully follow Step 1 to 5 and check the screenshot below.

    Your screenshot should show:

    • your notebook.jl file opened in VSCode is visible. 
    • your latest plot image and slider are visible in your Pluto notebook. 
    • your file explorer showing all of your files and directories. 
    • your full screen, including your taskbar (for Windows and Linux) / dock (for MacOS).

    If yours match with the expected output, congratulations! You have finished the tutorial 🎉
